(forewing length 
<quantity box="[723,854,1610,1636]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.5" metricValueMax="1.6" metricValueMin="1.4" pageId="19" pageNumber="244" unit="mm" value="15.0" valueMax="16.0" valueMin="14.0">14–16 mm</quantity>
) occurs in two forms. In the darker, more common form (Fig. 10) the forewing is reddish brown with the
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="20.[140,1108,954,1008]" pageId="20" pageNumber="245">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[140,304,954,976]" pageId="20" pageNumber="245">Figures 46–48.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName authorityName="Guenee" authorityYear="1852" box="[310,391,955,976]" class="Insecta" family="Noctuidae" genus="Hypotrix" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="20" pageNumber="245" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[310,391,955,976]" italics="true" pageId="20" pageNumber="245">Hypotrix</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Lafontaine &amp; Ferris &amp; Walsh" authorityYear="2010" box="[439,540,955,976]" class="Insecta" family="Noctuidae" genus="Anhypotrix" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="20" pageNumber="245" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[439,540,955,976]" italics="true" pageId="20" pageNumber="245">Anhypotrix</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
male genitalia. 
<emphasis bold="true" box="[690,717,954,976]" pageId="20" pageNumber="245">46</emphasis>
<taxonomicName authorityName="Smith" authorityYear="1906" box="[723,814,955,976]" class="Insecta" family="Noctuidae" genus="Ursogastra" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="20" pageNumber="245" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="lunata">
<emphasis box="[723,742,955,976]" italics="true" pageId="20" pageNumber="245">H</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis box="[755,814,955,976]" italics="true" pageId="20" pageNumber="245">lunata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<emphasis bold="true" box="[821,848,954,976]" pageId="20" pageNumber="245">47</emphasis>
<taxonomicName authorityName="Guenee" authorityYear="1852" box="[854,992,955,976]" class="Insecta" family="Noctuidae" genus="Hypotrix" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="20" pageNumber="245" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="purpurigera">
<emphasis box="[854,872,955,976]" italics="true" pageId="20" pageNumber="245">H</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis box="[885,992,955,976]" italics="true" pageId="20" pageNumber="245">purpurigera</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<emphasis bold="true" box="[998,1025,954,976]" pageId="20" pageNumber="245">48</emphasis>
<taxonomicName authorityName="Lafontaine &amp; Ferris &amp; Walsh" authorityYear="2010" baseAuthorityName="Barnes &amp; McDunnough" baseAuthorityYear="1910" class="Insecta" family="Noctuidae" genus="Anhypotrix" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="20" pageNumber="245" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="tristis">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="20" pageNumber="245">Anhypotrix tristis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="20.[140,1108,1082,1672]" pageId="20" pageNumber="245">
maculation sharply defined by dark-red lines. Th e medial area is similar in color to the remainder of the forewing and the postmedial line touches, or almost touches, the reniform spot. Superficially this form is most similar to 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Lafontaine &amp; Ferris &amp; Walsh" authorityYear="2010" baseAuthorityName="Barnes" baseAuthorityYear="1904" box="[778,944,1152,1178]" class="Insecta" family="Noctuidae" genus="Hypotrix" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="20" pageNumber="245" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="hueco">
<emphasis box="[778,944,1152,1178]" italics="true" pageId="20" pageNumber="245">Hypotrix hueco</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(see under 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Lafontaine &amp; Ferris &amp; Walsh" authorityYear="2010" baseAuthorityName="Barnes" baseAuthorityYear="1904" class="Insecta" family="Noctuidae" genus="Hypotrix" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="20" pageNumber="245" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="hueco">
<emphasis box="[1078,1100,1153,1178]" italics="true" pageId="20" pageNumber="245">H</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis box="[140,201,1187,1213]" italics="true" pageId="20" pageNumber="245">hueco</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
) and 
<taxonomicName authority="(Smith)" baseAuthorityName="Smith" baseAuthorityYear="1898" box="[266,506,1187,1214]" class="Insecta" family="Noctuidae" genus="Xestia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="20" pageNumber="245" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="bolteri">
<emphasis box="[266,409,1187,1213]" italics="true" pageId="20" pageNumber="245">Xestia bolteri</emphasis>
(Smith)
</taxonomicName>
, both of which occur with 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Lafontaine &amp; Ferris &amp; Walsh" authorityYear="2010" baseAuthorityName="Barnes" baseAuthorityYear="1904" box="[811,935,1187,1214]" class="Insecta" family="Noctuidae" genus="Hypotrix" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="20" pageNumber="245" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="alamosa">
<emphasis box="[811,833,1188,1213]" italics="true" pageId="20" pageNumber="245">H</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis box="[847,935,1187,1213]" italics="true" pageId="20" pageNumber="245">alamosa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. It differs from 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Smith" baseAuthorityYear="1898" box="[140,284,1223,1249]" class="Insecta" family="Noctuidae" genus="Xestia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="20" pageNumber="245" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="bolteri">
<emphasis box="[140,284,1223,1249]" italics="true" pageId="20" pageNumber="245">Xestia bolteri</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
in that 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Lafontaine &amp; Ferris &amp; Walsh" authorityYear="2010" baseAuthorityName="Barnes" baseAuthorityYear="1904" box="[375,501,1223,1249]" class="Insecta" family="Noctuidae" genus="Hypotrix" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="20" pageNumber="245" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="alamosa">
<emphasis box="[375,397,1223,1248]" italics="true" pageId="20" pageNumber="245">H</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis box="[413,501,1223,1249]" italics="true" pageId="20" pageNumber="245">alamosa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
has smaller reniform, orbicular, and claviform spots, and in lacking spiniform setae on the tibiae; 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Smith" baseAuthorityYear="1898" box="[654,798,1258,1284]" class="Insecta" family="Noctuidae" genus="Xestia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="20" pageNumber="245" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="bolteri">
<emphasis box="[654,798,1258,1284]" italics="true" pageId="20" pageNumber="245">Xestia bolteri</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is illustrated in 
<bibRefCitation author="Lafontaine JD" pageId="20" pageNumber="245" refId="ref13914" refString="Lafontaine JD (1998) Noctuoidea, Noctuidae (part), Noctuinae (part - Noctuini). In: Dominick et al. (Eds) Th e Moths of America North of Mexico fasc. 27.3. The Wedge Entomological Research Foundation, Washington, 348 pp." type="book" year="1998">Lafontaine 1998</bibRefCitation>
. Th e pale form of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Lafontaine &amp; Ferris &amp; Walsh" authorityYear="2010" baseAuthorityName="Barnes" baseAuthorityYear="1904" box="[432,561,1293,1320]" class="Insecta" family="Noctuidae" genus="Hypotrix" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="20" pageNumber="245" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="alamosa">
<emphasis box="[432,454,1294,1319]" italics="true" pageId="20" pageNumber="245">H</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis box="[473,561,1293,1319]" italics="true" pageId="20" pageNumber="245">alamosa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
looks like the specimens have been bleached, so the forewing is light orange with the maculation weakly defined by fine yellow lines. Th e dark and light forms frequently occur together and the two 
<typeStatus box="[942,1039,1364,1390]" pageId="20" pageNumber="245">syntypes</typeStatus>
of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Lafontaine &amp; Ferris &amp; Walsh" authorityYear="2010" baseAuthorityName="Barnes" baseAuthorityYear="1904" class="Insecta" family="Noctuidae" genus="Hypotrix" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="20" pageNumber="245" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="alamosa">
<emphasis box="[1078,1100,1364,1389]" italics="true" pageId="20" pageNumber="245">H</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis box="[140,228,1399,1425]" italics="true" pageId="20" pageNumber="245">alamosa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
represent a specimen of each form. The 
<emphasis box="[710,868,1399,1425]" italics="true" pageId="20" pageNumber="245">male genitalia</emphasis>
differ from those of other species in many features: the valves are tapered from the base to apex a slightly indented “neck” at the base of the triangular cucullus; the sacculus is very large with a rounded lobe projecting from the dorsal margin and the membranous saccular flap overtops almost the entire sclerotized part; the digitus is wide and truncated apically; the apical half of the uncus is broad and spatulate; the vesica has a mass of cornuti near the apex of the aedeagus, and the apical part of the vesica has four tight coils. In the 
<emphasis box="[185,360,1645,1671]" italics="true" pageId="20" pageNumber="245">female genitalia</emphasis>
the appendix bursae has four tight coils, corresponding to those
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="21.[140,1108,167,333]" pageId="21" pageNumber="246">in the vesica, and the ductus bursae is heavily sclerotized with a prominent posterior bulge to the left.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="21" pageNumber="246" type="distribution">
